    <h1>Structural view modes</h1>
    <p>AtlasArc keeps one dependency model underneath everything, but not every structural question deserves the whole model on screen. The graph and matrix can sit in a broad survey posture, a scoped root posture, a pinned-subject posture, or a cycle posture. The difference is worth knowing, because each one changes what stays on screen and what the info bar is really telling you.</p>
    <p>This is the page to come back to when the banner says Pinned, Cycle view, Cycles Only, or Boundary Matrix, and you want to know precisely what got narrowed and by which control.</p>

    <h2 id="survey-and-root-scope">Survey and root scope</h2>
    <p><strong>Survey</strong> is the ordinary project read. The Topology Graph shows visible packages as nodes; the Package Matrix shows the same packages as rows and columns. Filters, exclusions, rollup, and Hide isolated may all still be narrowing what you see, but nothing has been singled out. There's no selected structural subject.</p>
    <p><strong>Root scope</strong> starts from a package or source-folder subtree. Use Set as Root when the question is "what on earth is going on inside this area?" Root scope is a broad area reduction: it changes the visible universe, without making any one package the subject that every relation gets measured against. That distinction gets sharper in the next section.</p>
    <div class="placeholder-box">Screenshot: Set as Root scoping the Topology Graph to a single subtree</div>

    <h2 id="pinned-subject">Pinned subject reads</h2>
    <p>Pin a subject and one package, source folder, or subsystem holds the centre of the read. The view stops being "everything under this root" and becomes "what matters around this thing."</p>
    <p>In the Topology Graph, that's a single posture with live controls. The graph keeps the same subject perimeter on screen, while <strong>Direction</strong>, <strong>Neighbour links</strong>, and <strong>Mute cycles</strong> let you tune the read without starting over.</p>
    <p><strong>Neighbourhood</strong> and <strong>Boundary</strong> come up often enough in conversation that they're worth pinning down: they're useful shorthand for readings you can take, rather than stored modes or presets hiding somewhere in a menu. Turn neighbour links on when you want local blast radius. Turn direction on, muting cycles when the loops are shouting over the signal, when incoming and outgoing boundary traffic is the actual question.</p>
    <p>Pin a subject when the investigation has an owner: the package that keeps turning up in reviews, the subsystem boundary you suspect is leaking, the module whose traffic in and out someone is going to ask you to explain.</p>
    <div class="placeholder-box">Screenshot: pinned subject in the Topology Graph with Direction and Neighbour links active</div>

    <h2 id="boundary-matrix">Boundary Matrix</h2>
    <p>Boundary Matrix is that same pinned-subject posture, over in the Package Matrix. The subject row shows outgoing traffic from the subject to its neighbours. The subject column shows incoming traffic from neighbours into the subject. Neighbour-to-neighbour cells stay on screen as dimmed context.</p>
    <p>Set as Root is the tempting alternative here, so the two are worth separating. Root scope asks what's happening inside a subtree. Boundary Matrix asks what crosses the subject's perimeter, and whether the neighbourhood around it is tangled as well.</p>
    <p>When a boundary read comes out crowded, spend your attention on the subject row and column first. Dense neighbour-to-neighbour cells may well matter, but they stay context until they explain why the subject's boundary is under pressure.</p>
    <div class="placeholder-box">Screenshot: Boundary Matrix with the subject row and column against dimmed context cells</div>

    <h2 id="cycle-view">Cycle View</h2>
    <p>Cycle View pins the structural view to one detected cycle group. The Topology Graph expands the packages in that group with enough surrounding context that the loop is actually readable. The Package Matrix can show the same cycle group as a persistent matrix read.</p>
    <p>Use it once you've picked a strongly connected group and need it to hold still while you inspect edges, jump to source, export evidence, or flip between the graph and the matrix.</p>
    <p>It stays put until you clear it with the toolbar escape chip, and that persistence is deliberate. The selected group survives while you make a dozen small moves around it, which is what a real investigation tends to look like.</p>
    <div class="placeholder-box">Screenshot: Cycle View holding one cycle group, with the toolbar escape chip</div>

    <h2 id="cycles-only">Cycles Only</h2>
    <p>Cycles Only is a filter rather than a selected subject. It hides clean packages and clean dependencies so the current lens shows cycle-participating structure, and it can be active in the graph, matrix, Subsystems, and Hotspots wherever cycle participants can be meaningfully narrowed.</p>
    <p>The two read alike in the banner, which is exactly where people trip. Cycles Only answers "which of the visible things are caught up in unresolved cycle structure?" Cycle View answers "make this one group the structural subject." Different controls, different questions.</p>
    <p>Reach for Cycles Only when you're triaging across several cycle groups. Reach for Cycle View once you've chosen the group you're going to fix.</p>
    <div class="placeholder-box">Screenshot: Cycles Only narrowing the Package Matrix to cycle participants</div>

    <h2 id="choosing-the-right-mode">Choosing the right mode</h2>
    <p>When the banner is ambiguous and you just want the short version:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Use <strong>survey</strong> when you need a first map of the project.</li>
      <li>Use <strong>root scope</strong> when the question is confined to one package subtree (subsystem).</li>
      <li>Use <strong>pinned subject</strong> in the graph when you need local blast radius or boundary direction around one subject.</li>
      <li>Use <strong>Boundary Matrix</strong> when the subject's incoming and outgoing boundary traffic matters more than the whole subtree.</li>
      <li>Use <strong>Cycles Only</strong> when you are triaging cycle participants across the current visible model.</li>
      <li>Use <strong>Cycle View</strong> when one cycle group is the subject of the investigation.</li>
    </ul>
